WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:04.720
So I'm really excited. We're live on YouTube. If you were here for the Can Do pre-show,

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:09.680
you're welcome. That was an unexpected treat for everybody this spooky season,

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:15.440
but good morning, good afternoon, and I am so excited to have you all here with us today

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:19.280
as we kick off our Hiring Great Data Science Teams panel.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:23.280
My name is Jessie Mospach, and while I am currently a developer advocate with the Shiny

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:29.280
team here at rStudio, not that long ago, I was a data science job seeker who eventually got

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:33.680
their first data science job before moving into data science management.

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:37.279
So I know that we have a lot of ground to cover today with our panelists,

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:41.040
and I cannot wait for them to have the opportunity to share their advice

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.919
and experiences with you. So we have four fantastic panelists. Today, we'll be hearing

00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:51.279
from Rhonda Crate, principal data scientist at Boeing and adjunct professor at Washington State

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:56.720
University. We have Katie Schaefer, who is the manager of advanced analytics at Beam Dental.

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:00.959
We also have Jairus Singh, director of quantitative analytics at Pandora,

00:01:00.959 --> 00:01:07.599
and Yiwei Sun, VP of analytics at Amwell. So really an incredible, incredible panel

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:12.879
with a ton of advice and experience, and please feel free to put your questions in chat.

00:01:12.879 --> 00:01:16.720
We do have a list of prepared questions, but as always, we would love to hear from you as well.

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:23.199
So to kick things off, all of you come from data science backgrounds, and I'm really curious how

00:01:23.199 --> 00:01:29.360
that experience has helped inform your ability to manage a data science team. So I'll throw that

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:38.559
over to Yiwei first. Sure. So my background is in statistics. That's what I went to graduate school

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:44.639
for, and that was a really natural transition. So one of my first jobs out of grad school,

00:01:45.519 --> 00:01:48.639
the title is senior analyst, but I was working with healthcare data,

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:56.879
and the responsibilities and tasks involved R, SQL, working with large databases,

00:01:56.879 --> 00:02:01.919
doing analyses, basically all of the range of skills you would expect a data scientist

00:02:02.639 --> 00:02:09.600
to have today. So that experience, of course, was helpful to understand the technical side,

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:15.039
but I think just like any other job, whether it's data scientist or, I don't know, marketing

00:02:15.039 --> 00:02:22.399
associate, anything, the biggest and most important part in terms of getting to where I

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:29.759
was is learning how a business functions and just the day-to-day operations, understanding the

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:37.440
importance of emotional intelligence, working with other people, being organized, paying attention

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:43.039
to process. So those are, I think, more important than the actual data science technical jobs

00:02:43.039 --> 00:02:50.080
themselves. So it's just really being open and curious, as most, as all data scientists are, to

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:59.600
those other aspects of the job. Rhonda, how about you? I'd love to hear how,

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:03.279
you know, coming from a data background has influenced your management style.

00:03:04.399 --> 00:03:11.520
Sure. My management style is the first question. So I'm not technically a manager. I'm an associate

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:15.679
technical fellow, which is a slightly different role than management. We really take on the

00:03:15.679 --> 00:03:22.320
technical responsibilities of the team in guiding technical vision for execution. But I'll just kind

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:28.720
of add to my background is in statistics, and I have a needy cat right now. So I might just hold

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:35.039
her here, because otherwise she'll just keep jumping up here. And I have an undergraduate

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:40.399
and a graduate degree in anthropology, actually, which is really different than most people in this

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:47.679
field. And what it, especially like my anthropology degree, what happens is it just makes me realize

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:51.679
the importance of diversity on the team. Because people with different backgrounds and different

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:57.360
skills, whether you're from statistics, yes, economics, or, you know, environmental science,

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:02.639
everybody brings a unique perspective to solving real problems, right, and how we do that with

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:08.960
data. And so really, that's kind of what I look for in a team is, you know, do we have different

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:13.520
set of skills? How can we bring those skills and methodologies to solve problems that we have?

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:24.640
Jairus, how about you? Can you tell us a bit about your background and how that helps inform

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:32.320
managing a data science team? Yeah, definitely. So I came up through, you know, the team that I

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:37.119
now manage. So I started as an analyst on that team and sort of worked my way up to be in charge

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:42.480
of it now. And I think the biggest thing is that when you've done the work yourself, it gives you a

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:51.200
very, I think, good idea of how to ask people to do that work. And I try to be sort of like the boss,

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:55.279
like it, I think it's easy for me to ask myself, like, what was my ideal boss when I was an

00:04:55.279 --> 00:04:59.839
analyst? And then how do I try to become that? And I think it works well when you've done the work,

00:04:59.839 --> 00:05:04.640
because that vision tends to be more aligned with something that's achievable and good for

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:09.519
the business. But when you're managing people and you don't share those experiences, it's a lot

00:05:09.519 --> 00:05:15.040
harder to, one, formulate what that good boss looks like and then also to become it. And in some cases,

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:19.440
it may be almost unreasonable, right? If you're in charge of a bunch of different groups of teams

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:24.000
with sort of competing priorities, you may need to make decisions that benefit one over the other.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.079
But having done the work and then having been in charge of the small team, I think I have a very

00:05:28.079 --> 00:05:33.359
good idea of what it entails and also how to make sure that it's communicated well and it maximizes

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:39.119
impact. So sort of being the person I wanted to have when I was doing it is how I go about it.

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:42.959
I think it's worked pretty well so far, but that's sort of my strategy. Yeah.

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:54.079
Cool. And then I guess, yeah, from my perspective, I would kind of echo everything everyone

00:05:54.640 --> 00:06:01.600
just said. I'd say some ads there would be coming from a PhD program or academia. I think I'm more

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:07.279
sensitive on the hiring front to the skill set that they bring, even though oftentimes they will

00:06:07.279 --> 00:06:14.239
lack an actual job experience outside of academia. Just thinking through their experience as

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:20.000
job experience is really important. And I think they can be valuable skill sets to the team,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.679
but then also knowing kind of the skill gaps that they'll come with, right, since they have not

00:06:23.679 --> 00:06:29.200
worked in more of an industry setting. And then I think one thing I didn't appreciate in my old job

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:33.519
that I do appreciate in my new job. So my old job, I was a data scientist. There was no really

00:06:33.519 --> 00:06:38.079
analytics team. It was more of a consulting firm. My new job, I started out managing the analytics

00:06:38.079 --> 00:06:43.519
team. So I think finally I've gotten kind of a full circle lens of how those two teams can

00:06:43.519 --> 00:06:48.000
really complement one another, data science and analytics, the differences and kind of the

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:54.959
complementary nature between the two. Yeah. So I'd say that definitely informs my hiring

00:06:54.959 --> 00:06:59.920
of data scientists, knowing, hey, where do we want to take and pick up some of the work that

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:04.480
the analysts have done and how will those two teams and two folks work together? So.

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:08.959
Yeah, that's really great. And you've kind of cued us up for this next question. So I'm going

00:07:08.959 --> 00:07:15.440
to start with you, Katie, but I'd really love to hear. I know that everyone watching has questions

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:20.000
about this, and I know we all have experience with this, but starting with Katie, how do you feel

00:07:20.079 --> 00:07:24.799
or what do you feel are the best ways to assess a candidate's technical ability?

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:32.959
Yeah. So a lot of different options for this, of course. I think my goal as a hiring manager

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:39.679
is just, again, to your first question, right, having done the work yourself to at least some

00:07:39.679 --> 00:07:43.760
degree, I think allows you to just assess in some of their answers. Do they know what they're

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:48.079
talking about or is there kind of a level of, are they reaching a little bit too far on some of the

00:07:48.079 --> 00:07:54.799
skills? So I think that my technical experience helps with that, but I think one thing we do here

00:07:54.799 --> 00:08:00.799
at BEAM is we have a take-home test, simulated data. I think it is really important to assess

00:08:00.799 --> 00:08:04.079
those technical skills in an interview, but I think the one thing that I'm really not a fan of

00:08:04.079 --> 00:08:10.239
is kind of, to a point, I think certain more traditional like whiteboarding or brain teaser

00:08:10.239 --> 00:08:14.399
questions in interviews, I think at a certain point they kind of just measure performance under

00:08:14.399 --> 00:08:20.399
duress versus performance. So I think there's a happy medium between whether you're doing kind of

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:28.320
a live technical interview, live coding, making that productive and worth the time in terms of

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:33.679
assessing the skills you want to assess. Take-home is certainly another route that I've become a fan

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:38.400
of, but I've seen the kind of more live technical interviews done well and then some maybe not so

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:43.200
well where, you know, folks might have missed out on some good candidates just because they asked a

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:48.880
brain teaser that the person didn't get in those five minutes. So that's kind of my quick take.

00:08:52.559 --> 00:08:59.200
I'll kind of follow up. So I'm a huge fan of them basically talking about what they're

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:04.479
passionate about and describing situations where they've actually applied it, and some of the

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:09.840
key criteria, you know, that we probably look for in some of those answers are like,

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:14.239
you know, is somebody coming up to you and asking you for advice on how to solve these problems,

00:09:14.239 --> 00:09:20.400
right? Are you being a mentor to somebody else? Because that's usually, you know, a way that you

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:23.440
can share your skills with somebody else. That means you're confident enough to

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:28.159
to demonstrate your skills and then share that with somebody else and basically teach, right?

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:34.880
Also your, you know, your ability to describe it in a technical manner in a situation which

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:39.919
you applied it because honestly, like, you know, people come from a variety of different backgrounds.

00:09:39.919 --> 00:09:44.000
There's a whole bunch of different language that different backgrounds use to describe the same

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.479
processes. And so, you know, I really like the approach of asking them to describe a situation

00:09:50.479 --> 00:09:56.159
that they've been in, what was the outcome of that, and really describe the result in a technical

00:09:56.159 --> 00:10:01.599
format. And you can usually tell when somebody's passionate about something and let them kind of

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:06.159
pursue their passions a little bit. But at the same time, making sure that

00:10:06.719 --> 00:10:08.559
the skills that we need for the job, right?

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:18.880
I agree. Technical exercise is really important. I've always used them. It's, you know, it's

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.880
it's really the only way you can quickly and accurately assess the technical skills.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:34.559
So I think it's required. Also, just, you know, the basic integrating and job seeking 101

00:10:34.559 --> 00:10:41.039
expectations, you know, well put together resume, of course, you know, no typos, things like that,

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:49.200
things they teach you over and over again. And then over time, at least I like to think I've

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:54.719
developed like a intuition also, you know, it's well, it's more than intuition. It's on the

00:10:54.719 --> 00:10:59.119
resume. It's also in the actual interview process themselves. You can start to assess

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:06.239
to the extent, you know, that person's really curious and passionate about the work itself.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:16.640
So curiosity and energy to me are my number one and two traits that I look for. You know,

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:23.919
if you've only learned how to write R on the, you know, for a couple of years or in grad school,

00:11:24.799 --> 00:11:30.159
I think you can pick those things up, but you can't you can't teach someone to be really curious

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:38.080
and really energetic, you know. Yeah. And then finally, when we do start having technical

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:43.359
discussions, I think this is reflected in what Rhonda said, you know, it's a matter of

00:11:44.159 --> 00:11:47.440
does this person know what they're talking about? And so I listen for

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:52.559
are they being specific in what they're describing? If they start speaking in generalities

00:11:52.559 --> 00:11:57.440
and, you know, vague answers, you know, pretty quickly, they don't really,

00:11:58.239 --> 00:12:00.080
they aren't really well suited for this kind of job.

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:08.000
For sure, yeah. I'm going to echo a lot of things that were said. I'm on team take home as well,

00:12:08.239 --> 00:12:13.359
I hate doing brain teasers in interviews or even asking people to do them. It's,

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:18.559
I don't know, it feels like torture a lot of the time. But a plea for hiring managers out there,

00:12:18.559 --> 00:12:22.880
you know, try to make sure that you're asking sort of as little of folks that you can to get

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:27.520
a good assessment on them to just be respectful of their time. Because what happens is, and I think

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:31.280
it works in your favor, because you have some very bright folks out there who are like, hey,

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:35.200
you know, I don't know if I need to invest four hours into this when I have two offers.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.880
So you're going to turn away folks who, you know, really do know what they're doing, if you make it

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:44.479
too sort of heavy. And the opposite logic, which I don't agree with as well, if they really cared,

00:12:44.479 --> 00:12:48.799
they would sink in all this time and energy. And I just don't agree with that. But for us,

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:52.400
you know, I think there's a big concern that, well, what if they get a lot of help on the

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:56.640
take home, you're not really assessing their ability. So we like to ask a lot of follow up

00:12:56.640 --> 00:13:01.200
questions during the interviews. And we usually use one of our interviews to say, okay, you made

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:04.719
this decision here, you made this choice, or using this technique, can you tell me a little

00:13:04.719 --> 00:13:09.520
more about it? And then we're doing what you said, you know, is this something that your friend told

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:13.599
you to do, and you have no idea how the technique works, and you can't answer questions? Or is it

00:13:13.599 --> 00:13:17.599
something that you have knowledge of? So that's how we sort of try to bring that all together in

00:13:17.599 --> 00:13:23.359
our interview process. Yeah, that's really interesting. A lot of great, great perspectives

00:13:23.359 --> 00:13:28.080
here. And we've had a question from the audience that really dovetails nicely with this. So I'd

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:34.400
be really curious, if you change the way that you assess a candidate based on their kind of

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:39.200
educational background. So for example, you know, data science degrees are now a thing that people

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:44.479
can get. But if someone comes from a quantitative background, computer science, statistics, data

00:13:44.479 --> 00:13:51.039
science, versus someone coming from, you know, just a non quantitative background, education,

00:13:51.039 --> 00:13:57.679
or, you know, policy or literature, do you change how you assess that individual in an interview?

00:13:58.479 --> 00:14:02.880
Or, or no, maybe everybody's a no, but I'd be really curious if there's anything,

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:05.760
how you kind of may approach that differently, if at all.

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:13.840
I'd say that the first thing that sticks out to me is a little bit less of what I do kind of where

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:18.400
the conversation heads, but to me, it's really important you, whatever your applicant management

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:22.400
system is, it's really important that you're keeping up with the recruiting, like the lead

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:27.359
recruiter on it to make sure that person gets an interview. That's what I found to be the most

00:14:27.359 --> 00:14:32.479
crucial way in which I step in, which I typically wouldn't is just giving the head recruiter that

00:14:32.479 --> 00:14:36.479
like, commenting when we see the application and staying stupor on top of it myself,

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:40.960
because it's a little bit harder sometimes for them to spot like, Oh, well, this person with

00:14:40.960 --> 00:14:46.479
this non traditional background has the skills you want or not. So I just make sure that I get

00:14:46.479 --> 00:14:51.599
a chance to talk to that person. If I see that they've got some components that are maybe

00:14:51.599 --> 00:14:58.320
non traditional, but speak to their skill set. Yeah, and I'll kind of add that as somebody who

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:03.679
comes from a more non traditional background, right? I graduated with a liberal arts degree,

00:15:03.679 --> 00:15:10.719
and then I got my stat degree. But I will say like, personally, as I entered job interviewing,

00:15:10.719 --> 00:15:16.000
I was worried that my anthropology degree would actually set me back. But the reality, I mean,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:22.239
still had a stat, like I still have a master's in stats. But the reality is, it brought an element

00:15:22.239 --> 00:15:28.640
that differentiated me from the candidates. And I will say, at Boeing, everybody gets the same

00:15:30.159 --> 00:15:34.400
opportunity of interview for that step. So everybody gets the same question. So as far

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:38.640
as that goes, that that's a standardized process that our HR has developed, right.

00:15:38.799 --> 00:15:46.080
But I would encourage like any people that just have a solid, like science background to go out

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:52.880
and discover the liberal arts, because it can only make you better, right? That's my personal view.

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:58.479
I love that, right. So if you're coming from a quantitative background, go out, discover,

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:04.320
you know, do things outside of your educational background. So this really ties into a question,

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:08.799
and I'd love to start with you, Jairus. Skills like empathy and communication are often

00:16:08.799 --> 00:16:14.400
mentioned as like absolute must-haves for data scientists. But how do you know a candidate has

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:21.840
these skills? Yeah, I went through this great training at work a while ago. And it was sort

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:26.479
of a generalist training. It was not for hiring technical roles. It was just hiring in general.

00:16:26.479 --> 00:16:30.880
And they went over a really good framework for asking behavioral questions. And what I thought

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:36.159
was so unusual about it was that like the questions to me seem to have obvious answers.

00:16:36.159 --> 00:16:41.200
But if you ask 10 people or 10 data scientists, you're going to get rid of three of them because

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:45.440
they're not going to give you the answer that that you would want. And so what we do is we

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:50.400
sort of ask these, we put them in situations that are sort of undesirable. And I don't mean

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:54.799
literally in the interview. I mean, we ask them about situations that are undesirable. You know,

00:16:54.799 --> 00:16:59.919
you've gotten a vague request from a stakeholder, and we see how they deal with those situations.

00:16:59.919 --> 00:17:05.280
And I think folks who deal well with that, you know, first say, okay, you know, I get that this

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:09.839
happens on the job, and I will work with them to come to an answer. But there's always a subset of

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:14.880
folks who kind of put it back on you and is like, well, isn't your job to prevent these things from

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:19.439
happening? Or like, why would I be in this position? And it's, you know, as much as I'd

00:17:19.439 --> 00:17:24.560
love to live in a world in which it never happens, it always happens. And so it's kind of an easy way

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:28.400
I've found to ask those behavioral questions about, you know, difficult situations that

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:33.280
involve working with people or communicating things to people, and seeing sort of how flexible

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:39.359
data scientist applicants can be in their answers. So it was funny to me, because when I first learned

00:17:39.359 --> 00:17:43.280
these, I'm like, well, no one's going to say, like, I shouldn't do that, or that's not my job.

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:47.599
But you end up picking up a few people who genuinely do feel that way. And, you know,

00:17:47.599 --> 00:17:51.680
I'm sure they're a great fit for another role out there. But that role isn't one of ours.

00:17:52.079 --> 00:17:57.119
Yeah, for sure. And, you know, it's kind of nice to get to that point where, you know, right,

00:17:57.119 --> 00:18:03.760
like, you don't want to pull a candidate along if they're not a good fit. So as we're talking about

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:09.040
hiring, I'd love to hear from you to kick things off in terms of how do you know when it's time

00:18:09.040 --> 00:18:13.839
to grow your data science team? And kind of to piggyback off of that, what strategies do you

00:18:13.839 --> 00:18:19.280
employ when you're growing your data science team? And what strategies do you employ when you're

00:18:19.839 --> 00:18:22.160
growing your team?

00:18:25.839 --> 00:18:31.040
Everywhere I've been, it's always, well, I've always been hired because they needed to grow

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:38.880
the team. So they hired me to grow the team. So it's, it's all the answer is always pretty much

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:46.079
most, you know, most for most firms that are data rich, obviously could stand to use more data

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:53.439
scientists. But, you know, to answer your question directly, it's really a matter of demand,

00:18:53.439 --> 00:18:59.680
right? Last I've been doing this for a long time, and we just never have enough data scientists.

00:19:00.959 --> 00:19:06.719
The type of teams that I've managed have always been internal support and external support,

00:19:06.719 --> 00:19:13.839
